T1  - When do Interlocks Matter? Institutional Logics and the Diffusion of Multiple Corporate Governance Practices
AU  - Shipilov, Andrew V.
AU  - Greve, Henrich R.
AU  - Rowley, Timothy J.
Y1  - 2010/08/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.52814614
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2010.52814614
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 846
EP  - 864
VL  - 53
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Despite the wealth of research on the origins of institutions, little is known about how institutions and their underlying logics are extended following initial diffusion. We argue that institutional extension happens through multiwave diffusion of related practices that is such that an organization's adoption of practices from an institutional logic implies its acceptance of the logic. This makes organizational adoption of subsequent practices sharing the same logic more likely, irrespective of these practices' adoptions by the organization's network contacts. We show evidence of such effects though analyzing the diffusion of governance practices related to the logic of board reform in Canada.
AB  - Despite the wealth of research on the origins of institutions, little is known about how institutions and their underlying logics are extended following initial diffusion. We argue that institutional extension happens through multiwave diffusion of related practices that is such that an organization's adoption of practices from an institutional logic implies its acceptance of the logic. This makes organizational adoption of subsequent practices sharing the same logic more likely, irrespective of these practices' adoptions by the organization's network contacts. We show evidence of such effects though analyzing the diffusion of governance practices related to the logic of board reform in Canada.
